  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Total contract obligations in Michigan are $4.8B for FY2026 to date. Obligations fell 28.1% year over year, and the state has recorded 135,288 awards with an average award size of $35.1K. Michigan obligations peaked at $9B in FY22 and have since declined through $8.4B in FY23, $8B in FY24, and $6.6B in FY25 to the current $4.8B in FY26. The Department of Defense and the General Services Administration are the largest buyers in the state at $2.3B and $1.8B respectively. Major contractors receiving obligations include GENERAL DYNAMICS LAND SYSTEMS INC. at $1.1B, FORD MOTOR CO at $608M, and GENERAL MOTORS LLC at $592M. Industry concentrations include Automobile Manufacturing at $1.7B and Military Armored Vehicle, Tank, and Tank Component Manufacturing at $1.1B. These figures represent contract obligations only and cover FY2026 to date rather than a full fiscal year.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How have federal obligations in Michigan changed over recent years?",
        "body": "Obligations moved from $6.8B in FY21 up to $9B in FY22, then declined to $8.4B in FY23 and $8B in FY24, followed by $6.6B in FY25 and $4.8B in FY26. Year over year, obligations fell 28.1% for the current fiscal year to date."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Which agencies and vendors account for the largest shares of spending?",
        "body": "The Department of Defense accounts for $2.3B of obligations and the General Services Administration accounts for $1.8B. Top vendors include GENERAL DYNAMICS LAND SYSTEMS INC. with $1.1B, FORD MOTOR CO with $608M, and GENERAL MOTORS LLC with $592M."
      }
    ]
  },
